(NULL, "A book is the work of a mind, doing its work in the way that a mind deemsbest.  That's dangerous.  Is the work of some mere individual mind likely toserve the aims of collectively accepted compromises, which are known in theschools as 'standards'?  Any mind that would audaciously put itself forth towork all alone is surely a bad example for the students, and probably, ifnot downright antisocial, at least a little off-center, self-indulgent,elitist.  ... It's just good pedagogy, therefore, to stay away from suchstuff, and use instead, if film-strips and rap-sessions must besupplemented, 'texts,' selected, or prepared, or adapted, by realprofessionals.  Those texts are called 'reading material.'  They are theacademic equivalent of the 'listening material' that fills waiting-rooms,and the 'eating material' that you can buy in thousands of convenient eatingresource centers along the roads.		-- The Underground Grammarian", NULL),
